The air veſſels conſiſt of a pipe, called the trachea;
one end of which opens into the throat, and commu-
nicates with the atmoſphere amtoſphere by the noſtrils and mouth;
the other divides into branches which go to every part
of the lungs, and whoſe ends open into ſmall cavities,
or cells.

The whole of this motion is called reſpiration:
when the air is paſſing in, it is called inſpiration;
when it is thrown out, expiration.
